text: Dear Friend,
label: BODY

text: Welcome to "This Week in Congress." I hope you find this newsletter useful.
label: BODY

text: Talking to Senior Citizens about Improvements to Medicare
label: BODY

text: On Friday, I visited the Senior Center in Hays to talk to senior citizens about passage of the Medicare Improvements for
label: BODY

text: Patients and Providers Act, H.R. 6331. This legislation, which passed the House in June and has since become law,
label: BODY

text: eliminated scheduled reductions in Medicare physician payments, extended physical therapy caps and delayed
label: BODY

text: reductions in pharmacy reimbursement rates. Passage of this legislation was critical for Kansans as it allows hospitals,
label: BODY

text: doctors, physical therapists and pharmacists to continue serving the more than 114,000 Medicare recipients in the First
label: BODY

text: District.
label: BODY

text: I was joined at the Senior Center by David Wilson, president of AARP Kansas; Dr. Michael Machen of Quinter, president
label: BODY

text: of the Kansas Society of Health System Pharmacists; Jim Rorstrom of Hays; Fred Lucky, with the Kansas Hospital
label: BODY

text: Association; and Dave Sanderson of Salina, with the Kansas Physical Therapy Association. These experts were able to
label: BODY

text: explain to folks how the legislation affected their profession and answered questions about what the new law means for
label: BODY

text: Medicare recipients. Also discussed during the event was the AARP "Divided We Fail Pledge." This is a congressional
label: BODY

text: pledge asking the nation's leaders to commit to working in a bipartisan way to provide Americans with actions and
label: BODY

text: answers on health and long-term financial security. This is a pledge I strongly support and have signed my name to.
label: BODY

text: Congressman Jerry Moran

text: I enjoyed speaking to many of the seniors gathered for lunch, as well as Ernie Kutzley of Topeka, AARP Kansas; Mary
label: BODY

text: Tritsch of Topeka, AARP Kansas; Gerald and Dianna Schmitt of Wichita, AARP volunteers; Alberta Klaus of Hays,
label: BODY

text: president of AARP chapter in Hays; and Dan Morin with the Kansas Medical Society. Special thanks to Alice Herman,
label: BODY

text: director of the Meal Site, for hosting the forum. Click here to view photos from the event.

text: Visiting North Central Kansas
label: BODY

text: On Monday, I visited several communities in north central Kansas. While in Blue Rapids, I visited the State Bank,
label: BODY

text: Yungeberg Drug, the Post Office, Napa Auto Parts and several city offices. After my visit in Blue Rapids, I traveled to
label: BODY

text: Marysville to attend the Rotary Club meeting. Thanks to Marysville Rotary president, Kate Manley.
label: BODY

text: Also while I was in Marysville, I made a trip into the Marysville Advocate, a 122 year-old community newspaper. There, I
label: BODY

text: saw Sarah Kessinger, the new editor for the Marysville Advocate. She recently took over the paper from her parents,
label: BODY

text: Howard and Sharon. I commend her and the Kessinger family for working hard to keep this local publication serving their
label: BODY

text: community.
label: BODY

text: I also visited Hanover to talk with community members. There I visited with employees at Citizens State Bank, Hanover
label: BODY

text: Professional Pharmacy, the Post Office, Hanover Hospital, Andy's Hardware and Lumber, Crome's Market, Blue Valley
label: BODY

text: Insurance and Rural Water District #1.
label: BODY

text: In my visits with local residents, I was again reminded of my belief that Congress must immediately take up a
label: BODY

text: comprehensive energy plan to assist those families who are struggling with gas prices.
label: BODY

text: Learning about Cancer Prevention and Treatment with the American Cancer Society in Alma
label: BODY

text: On Monday, I met with Tonia Carlson of Paxico and Lisa Benlon of Overland Park to discuss ways in which Congress
label: BODY

text: can help increase cancer screening and prevention treatments. Ms. Carlson is the grassroots leader of the First
label: BODY

text: Congressional District for the American Cancer Society. Ms. Benlon is a former State Representative who is now with the
label: BODY

text: American Cancer Society
label: BODY

text: One of the issues we talked about was colon cancer. This disease is one of the leading preventable causes of death in
label: BODY

text: the United States, with a five-year survival rate of nearly 90 percent when detected early. I am a sponsor of the
label: BODY

text: Colorectal Cancer Early Detection, Prevention and Treatment Act, which would help those most likely at risk of colon
label: BODY

text: cancer to receive screenings and treatment at an earlier age.
label: BODY

text: Speaking to Farm Bureau Members in Wabaunsee and Osage Counties
label: BODY

text: This week, I spoke at the Wabaunsee County Farm Bureau Annual Meeting in Alma and at the Osage County Farm
label: BODY

text: Bureau Annual Meeting in Carbondale. I spoke to members about the 2008 Farm Bill and the need for Congress to pass
label: BODY

text: comprehensive energy legislation. Attending Farm Bureau meetings across our state allows me to learn more about
label: BODY

text: issues important to farmers and ranchers.
label: BODY

text: Speaking to the Kansas Agribusiness Retailers Association in Manhattan
label: BODY

text: On Tuesday, I joined the Kansas Agribusiness Retailers Association (KARA) for breakfast at their annual conference in
label: BODY

text: Manhattan. Before introducing Senator Pat Roberts, I explained my plan for solving our nation's energy challenges and
label: BODY

text: also talked about the 2008 Farm Bill. Both Senator Roberts and I talked about how Congress has become more urban
label: BODY

text: and explained the difficulty in getting members from urban areas to understand the importance of agriculture policy in
label: BODY

text: rural America.
label: BODY

text: I also expressed my condolences on the passing of one of KARA's outstanding leaders, James B. "J.B." Pearl. Mr. Pearl
label: BODY

text: was the founder of J.B. Pearl Sales and Services in St. Marys, which was recognized in 2003 as the National Ag Retailer
label: BODY

text: of the Year. My thoughts and prayers are with Mr. Pearl's family and friends. Thank you to President Tom Tunnel and
label: BODY

text: KARA for inviting me to speak.
label: BODY

text: Observing Chapman Rebuilding and Recovering
label: BODY

text: Congressman Jerry Moran
label: BODY

text: On Tuesday, I visited Chapman to observe the town's recovery efforts and to visit with their community members.
label: BODY

text: Chapman received extensive damage when a tornado touched down on the evening of June 12, 2008. While there this
label: BODY

text: week, I visited the Unified School District (U.S.D.) 473 offices, City Hall, Chapman Public Library where I spoke with the
label: BODY

text: Library Director Carol Frasure, Astra Bank, Londeen Hardware & Furniture Store, Insurance Store, Chapman Senior
label: BODY

text: Center and Shamrock Cafe.
label: BODY

text: I was very interested in visiting Chapman High School. I believed it was important to congratulate the school's
label: BODY

text: administration and teachers on beginning class this fall. The school faced tremendous circumstances following the
label: BODY

text: tornado and I wanted to commend them for starting school up as scheduled.
label: BODY

text: Visiting Garden City
label: BODY

text: Garden City Community College: On Thursday, I made a visit to Garden City Community College. I had a good
label: BODY

text: conversation with Dr. Carol Ballantyne, the president of the college. On my visit, I learned about the opportunity the
label: BODY

text: planned Sunflower coal-fired power plant expansion presents for training construction trades at the college. We also
label: BODY

text: talked about the Higher Education Act, education of health care professionals for southwestern Kansas and the TRIO
label: BODY

text: program.
label: BODY

text: St. Catherine Hospital: I also toured St. Catherine Hospital (SCH) in Garden City. SCH is an affiliate of Catholic Health
label: BODY

text: Initiatives, the largest Catholic not-for-profit health organization in the country. It is licensed for 132 beds, is an accredited
label: BODY

text: regional health care center and has a medical staff that consists of specialists in family practice, internal medicine,
label: BODY

text: obstetrics and gynecology, gastroenterology, ophthalmology, orthopedics, pathology, pediatrics, podiatry, psychiatry,
label: BODY

text: pulmonary medicine, oncology, radiology, general and thoracic surgery and urology.
label: BODY

text: During my visit, I had a great discussion with Scott Taylor, SCH President & CEO. We discussed Medicare billing and
label: BODY

text: reimbursements, pricing privileges for prescription drug programs, pay for performance of providers and charity care.
label: BODY

text: Following my visit with Mr. Taylor, John Yox, SCH Senior Vice President and Bonnie Peters, SCH Vice President for

text: Attending Fort Hays State University Foundation Board of Trustees Meeting
label: BODY

text: I serve on the Fort Hays State University (FHSU) Foundation Board of Trustees. Each year, the foundation helps make a
label: BODY

text: college education a reality for young people by distributing approximately $1.4 million in scholarships. On Friday, I
label: BODY

text: attended a board meeting in Hays about promoting educational excellence. I enjoyed meeting with the other board
label: BODY

text: members and President and CEO Tim Chapman. Congratulations to incoming chair Dr. John Tomlinson and job well
label: BODY

text: done to outgoing chair Kerry McQueen.
label: BODY

text: Annual Kansas State Fair Beginning This Week
label: BODY

text: The annual Kansas State Fair begins Friday and lasts through Sunday, September 14. The fair is the largest event in the
label: BODY

text: state and attracts some 350,000 people. Each year since being elected to Congress, I have attended the fair to gather
label: BODY

text: input and suggestions from Kansans to take back to Washington, D.C. The fair gives me an opportunity to meet many
label: BODY

text: people from all parts of the state to discuss current issues. After these discussions, I always have a fresh perspective on
label: BODY

text: the topics most important to Kansans.
label: BODY

text: As in years past, I will have a booth in the Pride of Kansas Building. Members of my staff will be available to answer
label: BODY

text: questions and provide information. I will also take part in several events at the fair, including the annual Kansas Farm
label: BODY

text: Bureau Leadership Breakfast on Saturday, September 6. I hope to see you and your family at the fair in Hutchinson.
label: BODY

text: Attending Labor Day Events
label: BODY

text: To celebrate Labor Day this year, I attended the 112th Annual Labor Day Celebration in Hoisington. Thanks to Brian
label: BODY

text: Harrison for participating with me in this year's parade.
label: BODY

text: I also attended the City of Chapman Labor Day Parade. It was encouraging to see the city's recovery efforts and their
label: BODY

text: commitment to continuing this parade which was first celebrated in 1909. Thanks to Phil Weishaar for organizing my
label: BODY

text: participation in the parade.
label: BODY
